{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566500"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:42:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:42:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18835"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18835"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.75,0.03,0.13,0.08,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11568"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79629"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11568"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18835"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64933"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"18"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5749"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11282"},{"type":"tags","id":"11293"},{"type":"tags","id":"12867"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27226"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27233"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79629","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79629"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA medical student observes a medication error during their clinical placement. The wrong dose of a medication was administered to a patient, but the error was quickly identified and the patient experienced no harm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first response to this adverse event?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Recognise the error and disclose openly to patient","Wait to see if any symptoms develop before taking action","Refer the matter directly to the healthcare complaints commission","No further action is required as the patient did not experience harm","Avoid discussing the error to prevent patient anxiety"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate first response is to \u003Cstrong\u003Erecognise the error and disclose openly to patient\u003C/strong\u003E. This aligns with the principles of open disclosure and good medical practice, which emphasise transparency and honest communication when adverse events occur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect responses can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWait to see if any symptoms develop before taking action\u003C/strong\u003E - Delaying action could potentially harm the patient and goes against principles of prompt disclosure and management\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERefer the matter directly to the healthcare complaints commission\u003C/strong\u003E - While reporting is important, it should not be the first response before addressing immediate patient safety concerns and disclosure\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo further action is required as the patient did not experience harm\u003C/strong\u003E - All medication errors require disclosure, documentation and review, regardless of whether harm occurred, to prevent future incidents\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAvoid discussing the error to prevent patient anxiety\u003C/strong\u003E - This conflicts with the principle of open disclosure and transparency in healthcare\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter disclosing to the patient, subsequent steps should include ensuring patient safety, documenting the event, reporting through appropriate channels, and implementing measures to prevent recurrence.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Open disclosure requires prompt acknowledgment and explanation of adverse events to patients.","Healthcare providers must take immediate action to rectify problems and prevent further harm when adverse events occur.","Proper handling of adverse events includes reporting, documenting, and implementing changes to prevent recurrence."],"references":["Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64933"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18835"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64933"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T11:49:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T11:51:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11568"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79629"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"18","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/18"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddd1\u200d\u2696\ufe0f","name":"Medicolegal","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67",